default26)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultSHOT
default haemovigilance scheme is an international field leader
default because it was one of the earliest, has detailed analysis and trending. T
defaulthe data 
defaultare
default widely used at international as well as national levels.  Many countries have developed haemovigilance schemes, particularly in 
defaultEurope
default, but the International Haemovigilance Network encourages all countries to set this up.  It is difficult to compare data between countries as data collection 
defaultand denominator data are variable
default.  
default27)
default&#xa0; 
defaultSHOT
default collects ‘near miss’ events where no harm came to the patient, but important lessons are learned from these observations. For example, for every wrong transfusion resulting from a wrong blood sample, there are about 100 ‘near miss’ events where the error was recognised
default before any transfusion took place,
default for example because the blood group previously recorded 
defaultfor the patient 
defaultwas different
default to the one associated with the current blood sample
default.
default28)
default&#xa0; 
defaultSHOT
default produces benchmarking data 
defaultannually 
defaultfor all participants
default,
default relating the number of reports to the 
defaultsize of the organisation as defined by the number of 
defaultblood components issued, and grouped geographically.  These show that the range
default of medians
default is 0.69 to 1.21 for the number of reports per 1000 components issued
default in the different sized organisations, with an overall range of 0 to 6.8
default reports
default. European and Canadian data are similar with 0.2 to 7.07 reports per 1000 units transfused or issued to hospitals.  A WHO Global Forum in November 2012 in association with the International Soiety of Blood Transfusion and the International Haemovigilance Network had representation from 46 countries. There is variable development of haemovigilance schemes hindered in many countries by lack of resources but also by a cultural fear of reporting adverse incidents.
